  "description": "¶Entry conditions Use a category only when you can:\nIdentify objects and morphisms between them. Define composition of morphisms that is associative. Provide identity morphisms for every object. If composition is undefined or not associative, do not use category theory.\n¶Definitions A category has objects, morphisms, identities, and associative composition. ¶Vocabulary (plain language) Object: a thing you care about (a set, state, type, or context). Morphism: a directed arrow or process from one object to another. Composition: doing one morphism after another. Identity morphism: the \u0026ldquo;do nothing\u0026rdquo; morphism for an object. ¶Symbols used ¶Symbols used f:A→Bf:A \\to B: a morphism from object AA to object BB. g∘fg \\circ f: compose ff then gg. idA\\mathrm{id}_A: the identity morphism on AA. ¶Intuition Categories are about processes between things, not just the things themselves. Objects can be types, states, or contexts. Morphisms are the allowed transformations. Composition means \u0026ldquo;do this, then that,\u0026rdquo; and associativity means the grouping does not matter.\n",
